Vice President Kamala Harris visited the Phillis Wheatley Community Center in Greenville, South Carolina to thank the community for their efforts in getting people vaccinated against COVID-19. She emphasized the importance of getting vaccinated as an act of love for one's neighbor and highlighted the barriers that people face in accessing vaccines, such as lack of transportation, childcare, and paid time off. Harris also addressed vaccine hesitancy and misinformation, reassuring people that the vaccines are safe, effective, and free. She urged everyone to encourage their friends and family to get vaccinated and emphasized the progress that has been made in combating the pandemic. Harris expressed confidence in the American people's ability to come together and achieve the goal of vaccinating 70% of American adults by July 4th.